{"type":"tool_execution_end","toolCallId":"call_e94d","toolName":"mcp","result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630025157","member_id":"C5","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C5","model":"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:3:C5","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C5","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\n\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\n\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\n\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \"all kinetic activity\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\n\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\n\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\n\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\n\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\n\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\n\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\n\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\n\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\n\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\n\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\n\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\n\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\n\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\n\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\n\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\n\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\n\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\n\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\n\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\n\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\n\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\n\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\n\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z","evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","storage_name":"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","size_bytes":1387,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z","evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","storage_name":"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","size_bytes":2081,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z","evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","storage_name":"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","size_bytes":2892,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z","evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","storage_name":"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z","evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","storage_name":"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","size_bytes":2150,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z","evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","storage_name":"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","size_bytes":4176,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\n\n## Main affirmative leads\n\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\n\n## Main defense leads\n\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\n\n## Preserved reporting files\n\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-5 ABC News source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-6 Guardian source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","label":"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture."},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","label":"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\n\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"D-3 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\n\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\n\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\n\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\n\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\n\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\n\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\n\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\n\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\n\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\n\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":3,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\n\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\n\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\n\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\n\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\n\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\n\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\n\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\n\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.","title":"Plaintiff source-search ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.","title":"Defense source-chain and search ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z","deliberation_round":3,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:3:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":894569,"role_id":"council","turn_number":21}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"}},"isError":false}
{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e94d","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630025157","member_id":"C5","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C5","model":"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:3:C5","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C5","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\n\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\n\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\n\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \"all kinetic activity\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\n\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\n\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\n\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\n\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\n\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\n\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\n\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\n\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\n\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\n\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\n\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\n\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\n\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\n\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\n\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\n\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\n\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\n\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\n\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\n\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\n\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\n\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\n\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z","evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","storage_name":"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","size_bytes":1387,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z","evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","storage_name":"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","size_bytes":2081,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z","evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","storage_name":"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","size_bytes":2892,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z","evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","storage_name":"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z","evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","storage_name":"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","size_bytes":2150,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z","evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","storage_name":"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","size_bytes":4176,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\n\n## Main affirmative leads\n\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\n\n## Main defense leads\n\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\n\n## Preserved reporting files\n\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-5 ABC News source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-6 Guardian source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","label":"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture."},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","label":"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\n\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"D-3 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\n\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\n\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\n\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\n\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\n\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\n\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\n\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\n\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\n\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\n\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":3,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\n\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\n\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\n\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\n\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\n\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\n\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\n\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\n\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.","title":"Plaintiff source-search ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.","title":"Defense source-chain and search ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z","deliberation_round":3,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:3:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":894569,"role_id":"council","turn_number":21}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782790093540}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e94d","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630025157","member_id":"C5","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C5","model":"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:3:C5","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C5","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\n\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\n\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\n\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \"all kinetic activity\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\n\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\n\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\n\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\n\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\n\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\n\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\n\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\n\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\n\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\n\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\n\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\n\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\n\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\n\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\n\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\n\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\n\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\n\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\n\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\n\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\n\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\n\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\n\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z","evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","storage_name":"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","size_bytes":1387,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z","evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","storage_name":"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","size_bytes":2081,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z","evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","storage_name":"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","size_bytes":2892,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z","evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","storage_name":"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z","evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","storage_name":"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","size_bytes":2150,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z","evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","storage_name":"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","size_bytes":4176,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\n\n## Main affirmative leads\n\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\n\n## Main defense leads\n\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\n\n## Preserved reporting files\n\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-5 ABC News source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-6 Guardian source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","label":"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture."},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","label":"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\n\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"D-3 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\n\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\n\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\n\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\n\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\n\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\n\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\n\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\n\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\n\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\n\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":3,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\n\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\n\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\n\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\n\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\n\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\n\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\n\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\n\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.","title":"Plaintiff source-search ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.","title":"Defense source-chain and search ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z","deliberation_round":3,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:3:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":894569,"role_id":"council","turn_number":21}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782790093540}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I need to examine the admitted evidence to make my decision. Let me first get the case details and list the evidence."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e94d","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_get_case","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":18942,"output":44,"cacheRead":2368,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21354,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782790091724,"responseId":"gen-1782790091-jtBNu7yVMsTpG1lubnby"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e94d","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C5\ncase_id: arb-ex07-20260630025157\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:3:C5\nremaining_ms: 894569\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex07-20260630025157\",\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\\n\\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\\n\\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\\n\\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \\\"all kinetic activity\\\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\\n\\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\\n\\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\\n\\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\\n\\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\\n\\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\\n\\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\\n\\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\\n\\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\\n\\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\\n\\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\\n\\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\\n\\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\\n\\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\\n\\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\\n\\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\\n\\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\\n\\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\\n\\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\\n\\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\\n\\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\\n\\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\\n\\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"storage_name\":\"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"size_bytes\":1387,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"unresolved-record-gaps.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"storage_name\":\"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"primary-evidence.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"size_bytes\":2081,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"primary-evidence.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"storage_name\":\"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"official-source-record.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"size_bytes\":2892,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"official-source-record.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"storage_name\":\"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"storage_name\":\"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"size_bytes\":2150,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"secondary-reporting.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"storage_name\":\"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"size_bytes\":4176,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\\n\\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\\n\\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\\n\\n\\\"This market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes\\\\\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\\n\\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\\\\\"Yes,\\\\\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\\n\\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\\n\\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\\n\\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\\n\\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nDisputed\\n\\nOutcome proposed: Yes\\n\\nNo dispute\\n\\nFinal outcome: Yes\\\"\\n\\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\\n\\nNotes:\\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\\n\\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\\n\\n\\\"Updated May 8\\n\\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\\n\\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\\\"\\n\\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\\n\\n\\\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \\\"Yes,\\\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\\\"\\n\\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\\n\\n\\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Secondary reporting\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\\n\\n## Main affirmative leads\\n\\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\\n\\n## Main defense leads\\n\\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \\\"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\n## Preserved reporting files\\n\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-5 ABC News source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-6 Guardian source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"label\":\"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \\\"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\\\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"label\":\"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \\\"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\\\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record\",\"label\":\"D-3 Official-source packet record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Official source record\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\\n\\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\\n\\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \\\"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\\\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\\n\\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\\n\\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\\n\\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\\n\\n## Unresolved official-source questions\\n\\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps\",\"label\":\"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Unresolved record gaps\\n\\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\\n\\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\\n\\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\\n\\nKnown record tension:\\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \\\"general pause\\\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"label\":\"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: ABC News, \\\"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\\\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \\\"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\\\"\\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \\\"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\\\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"label\":\"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Source: The Guardian, \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\\\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n- Headline: \\\"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\\\"\\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \\\"kinetic activity\\\" between the warring states.\\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\\n\\nCaptured official page text:\\n\\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\\n\\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\\n\\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\\n\\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\\n\\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\\nКвадрат Красної площі:\\n55.754413 37.617733\\n55.755205 37.619181\\n55.753351 37.622854\\n55.752504 37.621538\\n\\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\\n\\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\\n\\n8 травня 2026 року\\n\\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \\\"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\\\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\\n\\nRelevant captured text extract:\\n\\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\\n\\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\\n\\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\\n\\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\\n\\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\\n\\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\\n\\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\\n\\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\\n\\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\\n\\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\\n\\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\\n\\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\\n\\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\\n\\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\\n\\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\\n\\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\\n\\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.\",\"round\":2,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C3\",\"rationale\":\"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C4\",\"rationale\":\"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.\",\"round\":3,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\\n\\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\\n\\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\\n\\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\\n\\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\\n\\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\\n\\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4\",\"size_bytes\":1895,\"source_description\":\"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.\",\"source_url\":\"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171\",\"title\":\"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640\",\"size_bytes\":1904,\"source_description\":\"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may\",\"title\":\"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172\",\"size_bytes\":1687,\"source_description\":\"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.\",\"source_url\":\"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html\",\"title\":\"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3\",\"size_bytes\":1535,\"source_description\":\"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/\",\"title\":\"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f\",\"size_bytes\":1987,\"source_description\":\"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\",\"title\":\"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29\",\"size_bytes\":3066,\"source_description\":\"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026\",\"title\":\"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\\n\\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\\n\\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\\n\\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.\",\"title\":\"Plaintiff source-search ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-chain and search ledger\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z\",\"deliberation_round\":3,\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:3:C5\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":894569,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":21}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex07-20260630025157","member_id":"C5","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C5","model":"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:3:C5","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C5","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"By May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not merely an informal agreement, humanitarian pause, limited sector-specific ceasefire, or future framework.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, plaintiff has met the preponderance standard. The proposition asks whether, by May 31, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement constituting a general pause. It does not require a permanent peace, a thirty-day truce, or perfect compliance after announcement.\n\nThe governing rule is in PX-1: the market required a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, and it expressly allowed proof either from official announcements by both sides or from a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. PX-1 also excludes merely informal, humanitarian, Black Sea, energy-only, or similar limited agreements. That makes the decisive issues mutuality and scope.\n\nOn mutuality, the record is now strong. PX-2, the packet's official-source record, captures the Russian side through the Kremlin/Ushakov statement: Russia accepted the U.S. initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, with the understanding reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. PX-5, ABC News, reports Trump said he appreciated the agreement by both Putin and Zelenskyy, that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire-regime terms for May 9, 10, and 11, and that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire. PX-6, the Guardian, likewise reports the arrangement was confirmed by both sides, quotes Zelenskyy's May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language, and reports Russian confirmation through Ushakov. PX-7, China Daily/Xinhua, independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and quotes both Ushakov and Zelenskyy. PX-8, Ukrainska Pravda, reports Russia agreed to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and conduct the exchange, and notes Zelenskyy confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia.\n\nOn scope, the best evidence points to a general halt, not a sector carveout. PX-5 preserves Trump's statement that the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-6 reports the same \"all kinetic activity\" formulation and describes it as between the warring states. PX-7 again records that Trump said the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include suspension of all kinetic activity. That phrase is broader than Red Square, the Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or POW-transfer corridors. It is ordinary military-engagement language for a theater-wide pause in firing and strikes.\n\nThe defense is right that the arrangement was short, politically timed, and connected to a prisoner exchange and Victory Day. Plaintiff does not hide that. PX-5 says Putin had sought a short pause over Victory Day. PX-7 records Zelenskyy's Red Square decree and Russian MOD Victory Day language. PX-8 says Ushakov tied the initiative to Victory Day. PX-4, the unresolved-gaps packet, flags the same issues. But purpose and timing are not the same as operational scope. A ceasefire may be motivated by a prisoner exchange or holiday and still be a general halt if the announced commitment is to suspend all kinetic activity between the states for specified dates. The market excluded humanitarian pauses; it did not exclude a general ceasefire merely because it was temporary or paired with humanitarian exchange.\n\nNor do alleged violations defeat the proposition. The question is whether an official, mutual, publicly announced halt had been reached by the deadline. PX-1 says a qualifying agreement counts regardless of whether the ceasefire starts after the resolution date; it follows that compliance evidence is relevant to weight and scope, but not a separate requirement of flawless implementation. The cited sources include adverse context about prior violations and skepticism, but still report the agreement and the all-kinetic-activity term.\n\nSource weight is candidly mixed but preponderant. The direct Ukrainian official page and social post were not preserved as primary artifacts; direct U.S. social capture also remains imperfect. Yet the rule permits credible-media consensus, and the accepted evidence provides multiple independent reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports also include the defense's limiting facts, which makes their convergence more, not less, reliable: they were not one-sided market blurbs.\n\nThe preponderance answer is therefore Yes. By May 31, and in fact by May 8-9, the public record more likely than not showed Russia and Ukraine had officially and mutually agreed to a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic activity. Its short duration, Victory Day setting, prisoner-swap purpose, and imperfect source chain reduce weight, but they do not reclassify an announced all-kinetic ceasefire into a merely informal, humanitarian, sector-specific, or future-framework arrangement."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s evidence proves less than plaintiff says. It probably proves that public reporting used the word “ceasefire,” that Trump announced a three-day arrangement, that both sides acknowledged some arrangement, and that a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange was paired with it. But the proposition is narrower and harder: it requires an official, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, not a humanitarian pause or other limited arrangement.\n\nStart with the official materials. The Russian-side official source in D-3 frames the initiative as a ceasefire “for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” and describes the key agreement as the May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is not nothing. But it is exchange-purpose language, not a bilateral operational instrument setting a theater-wide stop to fighting.\n\nThe direct Ukrainian official decree is even narrower. D-1 is the official presidential decree page. It is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states a humanitarian purpose, permits the May 9 Moscow parade, and excludes only the Red Square coordinate box from Ukraine’s weapons-use plan for the duration of that parade. D-1 does not say Ukraine ordered a general halt across the front. It is powerful precisely because it is a direct official Ukrainian source: the preserved decree is a parade and Red Square targeting carveout.\n\nPlaintiff’s broadest scope evidence comes from secondary reporting, especially PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7, which preserve Trump’s “suspension of all kinetic activity” formulation and report Zelenskyy language that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The defense accepts that those exhibits have weight. They show why this is a close case. But they are still not the direct Ukrainian social post, direct Truth Social capture, or direct bilateral terms. Their own capture limitations say so. And the same exhibits preserve the limiting facts: Victory Day timing, prisoner-swap purpose, Red Square decree, Russian MOD Victory Day framing, prior violation history, and the absence of direct official/social source captures.\n\nImplementation evidence matters because the rule asks for a “general pause in the conflict,” not just a press label. D-2, the Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment, reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. It records mutual accusations of violations, claimed assaults, artillery and drone strikes, NASA FIRMS signatures showing hostilities decreased but did not cease, and persistent tactical combat missions. That evidence does not merely show imperfect compliance at the margins. It bears directly on whether the supposed arrangement ever functioned as a general pause rather than a short, loosely monitored, politically timed and exchange-linked truce framework.\n\nPlaintiff argues that violations cannot defeat a reached agreement. Sometimes that is right. A party can breach a ceasefire after making one. But the proposition here does not ask only whether a document or announcement existed; it asks whether the official arrangement constituted a general pause in the conflict. When the direct Ukrainian official act is Red Square-specific, the Russian official framing is prisoner-exchange-specific, and contemporaneous monitoring reports theater-wide continued operations, the better inference is not a qualifying general pause. It is a limited Victory Day/prisoner-exchange/parade-security arrangement, announced with broader diplomatic language, but not shown by a preponderance to be the kind of general halt the rule required.\n\nThe source-chain gaps reinforce that conclusion. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the U.S. source, battlefield monitoring, and post-period implementation statements. Plaintiff filled part of that with secondary reporting, but not the decisive primary terms. Plaintiff also did not submit a full direct Ukrainian source that says more than D-1. On this record, the broadest language is mediated through reporting; the most direct Ukrainian official source is narrow; and the best implementation evidence shows continued activity.\n\nThe council need not find that plaintiff fabricated anything. The more modest finding is enough: plaintiff has not carried preponderance on the qualifying element. A short announced ceasefire label, paired with POW exchange and parade security, is not necessarily a general conflict pause. The direct and adverse evidence makes the non-qualifying characterization at least as likely as plaintiff’s. Under the stated standard and exclusions, the proposition should be found not proven."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff asks for a Yes finding because the record makes the qualifying proposition more likely than not.\n\nStart with the rule. PX-1 did not demand a peace treaty, a permanent halt, or perfect performance. It required a publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause. It also allowed proof either through official announcements from both sides or through a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement had been reached. That last clause matters because the record contains exactly that kind of convergent reporting.\n\nThe central affirmative proof is consistent across independent exhibits. PX-5 reports Trump announced that Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire and that the ceasefire would include suspension of all kinetic activity, with agreement by Putin and Zelenskyy; it also reports Zelenskyy’s May 9-11 ceasefire-regime language and Kremlin confirmation. PX-6 reports both sides confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire, the prisoner swap, and the suspension of all kinetic activity. PX-7 independently reports Russia and Ukraine agreed to a three-day ceasefire, quotes Ushakov for Russian acceptance, quotes Zelenskyy for the May 9-11 ceasefire regime, and again records the all-kinetic-activity term. PX-8 and PX-2 support the Russian side of the same account. The evidence converges on mutuality, public announcement, dates before May 31, and a broad operational term.\n\nThe defense’s strongest point is that the arrangement was tied to Victory Day, a prisoner exchange, and a Red Square decree. That is true but not decisive. A general ceasefire can have a political occasion and a humanitarian purpose. The market excluded merely humanitarian pauses; it did not say a general all-kinetic ceasefire becomes non-qualifying because it is paired with a prisoner exchange. The question is scope. The record’s broadest and repeated scope term is not Red Square, Black Sea, energy infrastructure, or a POW corridor. It is suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine.\n\nD-1, the Ukrainian decree, is the defense’s best direct official document. But it proves a narrow implementation act: Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan during the parade. It does not say the broader ceasefire regime did not exist. It does not retract Zelenskyy’s reported May 9-11 ceasefire statement. Treating one specific decree as the exclusive Ukrainian commitment is an inference the document does not support.\n\nD-2, the Critical Threats/ISW assessment, is serious adverse evidence on implementation. It says limited operations continued, activity decreased but did not cease, and mutual accusations persisted. Plaintiff has never hidden that. But D-2 also repeatedly calls the period the May 9-11 ceasefire and describes continued operations as violations of it. It reports decreased hostilities, no large missile packages, and some sectors with no advance or no ground assaults. That is evidence of breach and imperfect observance; it is not better evidence that no official general ceasefire was reached. A party’s violations do not rewrite the announced agreement into a narrow carveout.\n\nThe source chain is imperfect. Direct Ukrainian social capture and direct U.S. social capture are missing. But preponderance is not certainty, and PX-1 expressly accepts credible-media consensus. Here, multiple accepted sources preserve the same official statements while also preserving the defense’s limiting facts. That balanced convergence gives them real weight.\n\nThe best reading of the whole record is this: by May 8-9, Russia and Ukraine had publicly and mutually accepted a dated May 9-11 ceasefire regime, announced as suspending all kinetic activity, connected to a large prisoner exchange and Victory Day, and then imperfectly observed. That is still a general pause in military engagement, not merely an informal agreement, sector-specific ceasefire, Red Square-only carveout, or future framework. On a preponderance standard, the proposition is true."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense closing is not that nothing happened. Something did happen: public reporting described a May 9-11 ceasefire, a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, and statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Plaintiff’s best evidence is the repeated “suspension of all kinetic activity” phrase in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7. That gives plaintiff a real case.\n\nBut the proposition is not “was there a ceasefire label?” or “was there a prisoner-exchange truce?” It asks whether Russia and Ukraine had officially reached a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, excluding humanitarian pauses and limited arrangements. Plaintiff must make that qualifying characterization more likely than not.\n\nThe record does not get there. The most direct Ukrainian official source, D-1, is narrow. It is not an order for a theater-wide halt. It is a humanitarian/parade decree permitting the Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade. Plaintiff calls that additive, but the problem is evidentiary weight: the direct Ukrainian official act is limited, while the broader Ukrainian commitment is preserved only through secondary reporting.\n\nThe Russian official source in D-3 is also limiting. It frames the initiative as a ceasefire for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange and identifies the key agreement as exchanging 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period. That is consistent with a temporary exchange-linked truce; it is not strong proof of a general pause in the conflict.\n\nD-2 is the record’s best implementation evidence. It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater on the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat persisted; that both sides made violation accusations; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Plaintiff says this is only breach evidence. But for this proposition, whether the arrangement constituted a general pause is the issue. Continued theater-wide operations and “activity did not cease” directly undercut that classification.\n\nThe source-chain gaps remain important. D-4 identifies missing direct captures of the Ukrainian social confirmation, the U.S. announcement, and fuller implementation records. PX-1 permits credible-media consensus, but it does not require the council to ignore the difference between broad secondary phrasing and narrower direct official acts.\n\nThe most balanced view is that the record proves a short, politically timed, Victory Day and prisoner-exchange arrangement, announced with broad diplomatic language and only partially observed. That is at least as likely as plaintiff’s qualifying “general pause” theory. Because plaintiff bears the preponderance burden, that tie or near-tie is a defense result. The proposition should be found not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:05Z","evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","storage_name":"20/209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","size_bytes":1387,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"41/41c18aa39f567ebb1de725235dace5b9de9a4cb6db1a481d7892ba6ab4b625ab","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"unresolved-record-gaps.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:28Z","evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","storage_name":"4f/4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"primary-evidence.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","size_bytes":2081,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"54/54e94624d24514b3f4a88caa1d4d27b7205b816158a39e94f6e9ae3a0c27b5d8","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"primary-evidence.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:59Z","evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","storage_name":"79/797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"official-source-record.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","size_bytes":2892,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"95/959b165782b3e76203a46f0e0ac7e0df6e44051c49775edaf7a85f90c1f45152","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"official-source-record.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:04:54Z","evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","storage_name":"b4/b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:42Z","evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","storage_name":"c8/c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"secondary-reporting.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","size_bytes":2150,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"cf/cf0c77f2fe5253983c14b901c93e8c226726f9b9400320c5eb3d163246fb2e16","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"secondary-reporting.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T03:01:23Z","evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","storage_name":"e2/e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:52:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","size_bytes":4176,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"f8/f841be6ff80db4ece1323f89060ea08eaa93c9ba1be1e008d1365dabc360d715","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market rule and resolution record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nMarket URL: https://polymarket.com/event/russia-x-ukraine-ceasefire-by-may-31-2026\n\nMarket title: Russia x Ukraine ceasefire by May 31, 2026?\n\nCaptured page text from web_fetch on 2026-05-11:\n\n\"This market will resolve to \\\"Yes\\\" if there is an official ceasefire agreement, defined as a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, between Russia and Ukraine by May 31, 2026, 11:59 PM ET.\n\nIf the agreement is officially reached before the resolution date, this market will resolve to \\\"Yes,\\\" regardless of whether the ceasefire officially starts afterward.\n\nOnly ceasefires which constitute a general pause in the conflict will qualify. Ceasefires which only apply to energy infrastructure, the Black Sea, or other similar agreements will not qualify.\n\nAny form of informal agreement will not be considered an official ceasefire. Humanitarian pauses will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nA peace deal or political framework will qualify if it includes a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement, effective on a specific date. Frameworks or agreements that outline terms for a future peace but do not include an explicit, dated commitment to stop fighting will not count.\n\nThis market's resolution will be based on official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; however, a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached will suffice.\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nDisputed\n\nOutcome proposed: Yes\n\nNo dispute\n\nFinal outcome: Yes\"\n\nSanitized page capture: market-page.txt\n\nNotes:\n- Purpose note: the arbitrations were intended to litigate the resolution condition independently of the dispute process and platform assertions made during that dispute.\n- The arbitration proposition tests the factual condition behind the final Yes resolution.\n- It does not ask whether Polymarket, UMA, or any resolver acted correctly.\n\nAdditional context block visible on the market page, checked 2026-05-11. This is Polymarket page context/assertion, not independent evidence that the proposition is true:\n\n\"Updated May 8\n\nA mutual agreement to halt military engagement between Russia and Ukraine has been publicly announced and confirmed by a consensus of credible reporting.\n\nWe’re aware of the dispute on this market. If a clarification is to be issued, it will be at 4:00 PM ET on May 8. If no statement is issued at that time, then there will be no clarification by the Polymarket team. The orderbook will be cleared at 4:00 PM ET, regardless of whether a clarification is made.\n\nThis market's language has been updated for clarity.\"\n\nStructured market-context paragraph from Polymarket page metadata, checked 2026-05-11. This is platform-generated context, not primary evidence:\n\n\"President Trump's May 8 announcement of a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine, effective May 9–11 to mark Russia's Victory Day and facilitate a 2,000-prisoner swap, has driven trader consensus to 100% \"Yes,\" as both Moscow and Kyiv publicly affirmed the mutual halt in military engagement—meeting Polymarket criteria for a general pause ahead of the May 31 deadline. This rare de-escalation follows February's Geneva trilateral talks and April reports of nearing a broader deal, signaling diplomatic momentum amid stalled frontline advances. Though temporary, official commitments outweigh prior short truces like Easter's. Realistic disruptions—mutual violation claims, abrupt escalations, or resolution disputes—remain possible but deemed improbable by traders risking real money.\"\n\nStructured metadata extract: polymarket-next-data-extract.json in the repository/source-captures, where present.\n\n\nCaution: these page-context statements should not be treated as proof of official mutuality, theater-wide scope, implementation, or credible-reporting reliability. They are after-the-fact platform assertions/context. The completed arbitration runs did not consider them and should not have considered them, because the experiment adjudicated the resolution condition independently of the dispute record.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"PX-2 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting","label":"PX-3 Secondary-reporting packet summary","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Secondary reporting\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis packet is still designed for open-record/search-enabled arbitration, but it now preserves excerpts from several credible reports and an ISW assessment.\n\n## Main affirmative leads\n\n- Reuters reported that Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire running May 9-May 11, with a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n- Guardian reported that the ceasefire and prisoner swap were confirmed by both sides and quoted Zelenskyy as saying that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- NPR reported that Zelenskyy and Kremlin aide Yury Ushakov both confirmed Trump's requested three-day ceasefire and prisoner exchange.\n- CBC republished Reuters reporting that both sides confirmed the agreement.\n- ISW assessed that Ukraine and Russia agreed to a three-day ceasefire from May 9 to 11 for the May 9 Victory Day parade and a prisoner-of-war exchange.\n\n## Main defense leads\n\n- Several sources frame the arrangement as tied to Victory Day, Red Square/parade security, and prisoner exchange.\n- Reuters, NPR, CBC, and ISW report continued accusations of violations or ongoing retaliatory activity around the ceasefire period.\n- The Russian official source describes the initiative as \"concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" This may support an argument that the arrangement is closer to a humanitarian pause than a general conflict pause.\n- The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is geographically narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade, though other reporting states Zelenskyy confirmed the broader ceasefire arrangement.\n\n## Preserved reporting files\n\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-trump-announces-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/reuters-may8-confirm-agreed-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/guardian-may8-confirm-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/npr-may9-trump-says-agreed.md`\n- `source-captures/cbc-may8-russia-ukraine-agree-three-day-ceasefire.md`\n- `source-captures/isw-may8-campaign-assessment-ceasefire.md`\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"PX-4 Packet record gaps and adverse tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-5 ABC News source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-6 Guardian source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","label":"PX-7 China Daily/Xinhua source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: China Daily / Xinhua, \"Russia, Ukraine agree to 3-day ceasefire, prisoner exchange,\" updated May 9, 2026. URL: https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports: Russia and Ukraine on Friday agreed to a three-day ceasefire and a swap of 1,000 prisoners.\n- It quotes Russian presidential aide Yuri Ushakov saying, at Putin's instruction, that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange between Russia and Ukraine was acceptable to the Russian side.\n- It quotes Zelenskyy on X saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement for a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- It reports Zelenskyy instructed the Ukrainian team to prepare what was necessary for the exchange.\n- It reports separately that Zelenskyy signed a decree excluding Red Square in Moscow from Ukraine's plan for use of weapons during the May 9 Victory Day parade for humanitarian purposes.\n- It reports Trump said on Truth Social that the truce between Russia and Ukraine would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a 1,000-prisoner swap from each country.\n- Adverse/limiting context: the article reports Russia's Ministry of Defense said all Russian military groupings in the conflict zone would completely halt combat operations during Victory Day celebrations from midnight May 8 to May 10.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a secondary wire-style report by Xinhua republished by China Daily. It preserves relevant statements but is not a direct official page, X post, or Truth Social page capture."},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","label":"PX-8 Ukrainska Pravda source capture","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Ukrainska Pravda, \"Kremlin says it has agreed to Trump initiative to extend truce until 11 May,\" Tetyana Oliynyk, May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports Russia agreed to support U.S. President Donald Trump's initiative to extend the ceasefire with Ukraine until May 11 and to carry out a prisoner exchange.\n- It identifies the source as Kremlin-aligned Russian news agency TASS citing Yuri Ushakov, an aide to Vladimir Putin.\n- It reports Ushakov said agreements on extending the ceasefire and conducting a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange were reached during phone conversations with the U.S. president's administration.\n- Adverse/limiting context: The article reports Ushakov added that Trump's initiative regarding the ceasefire and prisoner exchange was timed to coincide with Victory Day.\n- Background in the article reports Trump announced a three-day truce in the war between Ukraine and Russia; that Zelenskyy later announced the 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange scheduled for May 9 and confirmed the May 9-11 ceasefire with Russia; and that Ukraine officially permitted Russia to hold its Victory Day parade as part of the truce arrangement.\n\nCapture limitations: This is secondary reporting based on TASS/Kremlin-aligned source and other linked reporting. It is useful both as corroboration of Russian-side agreement and as adverse evidence of the Victory Day/prisoner-exchange framing."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"D-1 Official Ukrainian Decree No. 374/2026","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"D-2 ISW/Critical Threats continued-operations assessment","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record","label":"D-3 Official-source packet record","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Official source record\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThe market rule identifies two official-source paths:\n- official announcements from both Russia and Ukraine; or\n- a wide consensus of credible media reporting stating that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\n## Preserved official or official-adjacent materials\n\n### Russia: Kremlin / Yury Ushakov\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/kremlin-79702-ushakov-ceasefire-prisoner-exchange.md`\nURL: http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702\n\nThe President of Russia website published Yury Ushakov's comment: \"On the instructions from President of Russia Vladimir Putin, I confirm that the Russian side considers acceptable the initiative just proposed by US President Donald Trump concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange.\" It states that the relevant understanding was reached through telephone contacts with the U.S. administration and that the key agreement was a May 9-May 11 exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the ceasefire period.\n\n### Ukraine: Presidential decree through Ukrinform and inaccessible official URL\n\nSource capture: `source-captures/ukrinform-zelensky-decree-red-square.md`\nOfficial decree URL identified: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389\n\nDirect web access to the official Ukrainian presidential decree returned 403 in this environment. Ukrinform, Ukraine's national news agency, reported that Decree No. 374/2026 of May 8 was published on the president's official website. The reported decree authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. Ukrinform also reported that Trump had stated a three-day ceasefire would be introduced from May 9 to May 11 and that Ukraine had received Russia's agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange.\n\n## Unresolved official-source questions\n\n- The Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, is limited to Red Square targeting during the parade. It does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement.\n- Reuters, Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW report that Zelenskyy confirmed the ceasefire and/or that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11. Those reports are preserved in `source-captures/` but the underlying Telegram/X post is not independently captured here.\n- The Russian official text frames the ceasefire as concerning a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. That framing may matter under the market exclusion for humanitarian pauses and limited agreements.\n- The preserved public record includes repeated reports of alleged ceasefire violations and continued hostilities around related unilateral ceasefires. Whether that defeats the rule language is a merits question for the arbitrations.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps","label":"D-4 Packet record gaps and source-chain tensions","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Unresolved record gaps\n\nUpdated: 2026-05-18T21:34:58Z\n\nThis directory is suitable for open-record/search-enabled arbitration. It is closer to a closed-record packet than the original preliminary directory, but it remains insufficient for a clean closed-record replication.\n\nMaterial gaps before a closed-record run:\n- direct capture of Zelenskyy's Telegram/X confirmation of the May 9-May 11 ceasefire regime;\n- direct capture of the official Ukrainian presidential decree from president.gov.ua, which returned 403 here;\n- direct capture of Trump's Truth Social post or White House record, rather than media excerpts quoting it;\n- direct battlefield/monitoring evidence about whether hostilities paused generally or continued materially during May 9-May 11;\n- complete official Russian and Ukrainian post-period violation/implementation statements;\n- if relevant, UMA proposal/dispute transaction records or Polymarket comments explaining the dispute.\n\nKnown record tension:\n- The affirmative case has a wide credible-media consensus that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a May 9-May 11 ceasefire with suspension of kinetic activity.\n- The defense case has credible grounds to argue the arrangement was limited by its Victory Day, Red Square, prisoner-exchange, and alleged-violation context and therefore may not satisfy the market's \"general pause\" and non-humanitarian exclusions.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"PX-R1 Ukrainian decree does not negate broader truce","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"PX-R2 Implementation evidence treats activity as ceasefire violations","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."},{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","label":"PX-R3 ABC all-kinetic activity and mutual confirmation","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: ABC News, \"Trump says 3-day ceasefire, prisoner swap to occur between Russia and Ukraine,\" by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, May 8, 2026, 5:01 PM. URL: https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open/find.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- The article reports that President Donald Trump announced Friday that Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a brief three-day ceasefire and a prisoner swap following U.S.-mediated talks.\n- It notes adverse/limiting context: Putin had called for a short pause over Russia's May 9 Victory Day holiday and there was little expectation Putin would extend the ceasefire past Monday.\n- The article quotes Trump's social-media statement: \"This Ceasefire will include a suspension of all kinetic activity, and also a prison swap of 1,000 prisoners from each Country. This request was made directly by me, and I very much appreciate its agreement by President Vladimir Putin and President Volodymyr Zelenskyy.\"\n- The article reports that Zelenskyy confirmed Ukraine had received a prisoner swap offer from Russia and said it must be accompanied by a ceasefire; it also reports that the Kremlin confirmed it would observe the ceasefire, saying it had first been agreed to by Putin and Trump during a recent phone call.\n- The article quotes Zelenskyy: \"A ceasefire regime must also be established on May 9, 10, and 11,\" and reports he expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov said the agreement was reached during telephone contacts with the U.S. president's administration.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from an accessible web page, not a screenshot. It is secondary reporting, but it quotes and summarizes statements by Trump, Zelenskyy, and Kremlin aide Yuri Ushakov."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","label":"PX-R4 Guardian both-side confirmation and all-kinetic activity","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Source: The Guardian, \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May,\" Guardian staff and agencies, first published May 8, 2026. URL: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n- Headline: \"Russia and Ukraine confirm three-day ceasefire from 9 May.\"\n- Subheading states both sides confirmed a prisoner swap announced by Donald Trump along with suspension of all \"kinetic activity\" between the warring states.\n- The article reports that Trump announced a three-day ceasefire in the war between Russia and Ukraine from May 9 to May 11.\n- It reports that Trump said the ceasefire would include a suspension of all kinetic activity and a swap of 1,000 prisoners from each country, and that it was confirmed by both sides.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy confirmed Trump's announcement and the prisoner swap on Telegram, saying Ukraine received Russia's agreement to conduct a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange and that a ceasefire regime must be established on May 9, 10, and 11.\n- The article reports Zelenskyy thanked the U.S. president and expected the United States to ensure Russia fulfilled the agreements.\n- The article reports Russia confirmed the truce and POW swap; Kremlin adviser Yuri Ushakov said Russia accepted Trump's initiative concerning a ceasefire for a prisoner-of-war exchange between Russia and Ukraine.\n- Adverse context: The article notes Russia had previously announced a unilateral Victory Day ceasefire; Ukraine had offered a truce that Moscow ignored; both Moscow and Kyiv had accused each other of violating previous ceasefires.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extraction from a news article page, not the underlying Telegram/X posts or official Kremlin page. The source is secondary reporting with quoted statements and agency reporting."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","label":"DX-S1 Direct Ukrainian decree narrow scope","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Official website of the President of Ukraine, Decree No. 374/2026. URL: https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web open.\n\nCaptured official page text:\n\n# УКАЗ ПРЕЗИДЕНТА УКРАЇНИ №374/2026\n\nПро проведення параду в м.Москві\n\nВраховуючи численні прохання, з гуманітарною метою, окресленою в перемовинах з Американською стороною 8 травня 2026 року, постановляю:\n\n1. Дозволити 9 травня 2026 року провести парад в м. Москві (Російська Федерація).\n\nНа час параду (з 10 години ранку за Київським часом 9 травня 2026 року) територіальний квадрат Красної площі виключити з плану застосування українського озброєння.\nКвадрат Красної площі:\n55.754413 37.617733\n55.755205 37.619181\n55.753351 37.622854\n55.752504 37.621538\n\n2. Цей Указ набирає чинності з дня його підписання.\n\nПрезидент України В.ЗЕЛЕНСЬКИЙ\n\n8 травня 2026 року\n\nEnglish working summary: The official decree is titled about holding a parade in Moscow. It states that, considering numerous requests and for a humanitarian purpose outlined in negotiations with the American side on May 8, 2026, Ukraine permits the May 9, 2026 parade in Moscow and excludes the territorial square of Red Square from Ukraine's weapons-use plan for the duration of the parade, beginning 10:00 Kyiv time on May 9. It takes effect upon signing.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text capture from the official web page, not a screenshot or signed PDF. The text is official-page content and should be weighed as direct evidence of the decree's narrow subject matter."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","label":"DX-S2 Continued operations during ceasefire period","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Source: Critical Threats / Institute for the Study of War, \"Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026.\" URL: https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026. Retrieved 2026-06-30 UTC via web search/open.\n\nRelevant captured text extract:\n\nRussian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire. Both Ukrainian and Russian officials issued competing accusations that the other side violated the ceasefire on May 10. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky stated that Russian forces continued assaults in key directions and conducted artillery and drone strikes. Zelensky stated that Russian forces conducted more than 150 ground assaults, 100 artillery strikes, and almost 10,000 drone strikes between May 9 and 10. Zelensky noted that Russian forces did not conduct any large missile packages, however, and the Ukrainian Air Force reported that Russian forces launched only 27 Shahed, Gerbera, Italmas, and Parodiya drones between 0000 and 0800 local time on May 10, all of which Ukrainian forces downed.\n\nThe Russian Ministry of Defense similarly accused Ukraine on May 10 of violating the ceasefire by conducting eight ground assaults; 676 artillery, MLRS, and mortar strikes; and 6,331 drone strikes. Observed NASA FIRMS signatures from May 10 indicate that hostilities further decreased on May 10, but that activity did not cease. Russian and Ukrainian sources reported that the overall operational tempo across certain areas of the frontline continued to decrease on May 10 despite persistent tactical combat missions that violated the ceasefire. The prevalence of mutual accusations and continued localized activity throughout the second day of the ceasefire highlights that ceasefires without explicit enforcement mechanisms, credible monitoring, and defined dispute resolution processes are unlikely to hold.\n\nKey takeaway preserved on the page: Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day of the May 9-11 ceasefire.\n\nAdditional relevant page text: Russian forces continued limited offensive operations in Sumy Oblast on May 10 but did not advance. Russian forces conducted limited ground operations in the Kupyansk direction on May 10 but did not advance. A Ukrainian 10th Army Corps spokesperson reported that Russian forces did not conduct any ground assaults in the Kupyansk and Borova sectors on May 9, but continued FPV and fixed-wing drone strikes at a reduced pace. Russian forces continued shelling, drone strikes, and limited ground assaults in the Slovyansk direction and the Kostyantynivka-Druzhkivka tactical area on May 10 amidst the truce but did not advance.\n\nCapture limitations: This is a text extract from an accessible analytical report page. It relies on ISW/Critical Threats synthesis and cited underlying Russian, Ukrainian, and NASA FIRMS materials; those underlying footnote sources were not separately captured in this exhibit."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff’s burden is preponderance, and the proposition is narrow but not trivial. We do not have to prove a peace treaty, a permanent end to the war, or flawless compliance. We must show that by May 31, 2026, Russia and Ukraine had officially reached and publicly announced a mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict, rather than an informal understanding, a sector-only carveout, a humanitarian pause, or a future framework.\n\nThe current packet already identifies the real dispute. The market rule preserved in ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page requires an official ceasefire agreement, publicly announced and mutually agreed, and it expressly allows either official announcements from both sides or a wide consensus of credible reporting that such an official agreement was reached. That same packet cautions, correctly, that the market’s final “Yes” outcome and platform context are not independent proof. The case should be decided from the source record, not from platform say-so.\n\nOn that source record, plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. The preserved official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, contains the Russian side of the mutual announcement: the Kremlin-published Yury Ushakov statement confirms Russia considered acceptable the U.S. President’s initiative concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine and a prisoner exchange, and describes the relevant understanding as reached through contacts with the U.S. administration. The same case packet records the Ukrainian side through Ukrinform and associated reporting: Ukraine received Russia’s agreement to a 1,000-for-1,000 exchange, and a ceasefire regime was to be established on May 9, 10, and 11. The plaintiff will show this was not merely a future aspiration; it was a dated ceasefire period before the May 31 deadline.\n\nThe strongest record support is not the market page, but the convergence described in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW are summarized as reporting that both Russia and Ukraine confirmed a U.S.-brokered three-day ceasefire from May 9 through May 11, paired with a large prisoner exchange, and including a suspension of kinetic activity. That kind of cross-source confirmation matters because the market rule itself permits a wide consensus of credible media reporting where it states that an official ceasefire agreement between Russia and Ukraine has been reached.\n\nThe defense will have serious points, and plaintiff should meet them directly. The Russian statement frames the ceasefire around a prisoner exchange and Victory Day timing. The Ukrainian decree captured through Ukrinform is narrow as to Red Square targeting during the parade. The unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, also notes missing direct captures of Zelenskyy’s Telegram/X confirmation, the Ukrainian official decree page, Trump or White House source material, and battlefield-monitoring evidence about whether hostilities actually paused. Those gaps affect weight and source custody. They do not erase what the admitted packet already tends to show: mutually public confirmation of a dated May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement.\n\nThe decisive question will be scope. If the evidence ultimately shows only Red Square immunity, a POW-transfer window, Black Sea or energy-infrastructure limits, or a humanitarian pause without a broader halt in military engagement, plaintiff should lose. But if the full source record confirms what the packet says the credible reporting reported, namely a May 9-11 ceasefire regime suspending all kinetic military activity between the two states, then the arrangement was a general pause even though temporary, politically timed, and allegedly imperfectly observed.\n\nIn later evidentiary phases, plaintiff will seek to put the council on the strongest sources: the full Kremlin text; the direct Ukrainian presidential, Telegram, or X confirmation if accessible; full Reuters and other reporting preserved in the packet; ISW’s assessment; and adverse implementation materials concerning alleged violations. At opening, the record already gives the council the right lens: this case turns on official mutuality and general scope, not on whether the ceasefire ended the war or whether each side later accused the other of violations."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense opening begins with the market’s own limiting words. The proposition is not satisfied by showing that someone used the word “ceasefire,” that there was a prisoner exchange, or that a short symbolic pause was announced around Victory Day. The plaintiff must prove, by a preponderance, an official, publicly announced, mutually agreed halt in military engagement that amounted to a general pause in the conflict. The exclusions matter: humanitarian pauses and limited agreements do not qualify.\n\nThe current packet is enough to identify the dispute, but not enough to resolve it in plaintiff’s favor. The market-page record, ev_f841be6ff80d_market-page, gives the governing standard and also warns that the platform’s final “Yes” context is not independent proof. The case must therefore turn on the underlying source record: official mutuality, scope, and whether the arrangement was general rather than limited.\n\nOn those elements, the record is materially weaker than plaintiff’s opening suggests. The official-source record, ev_959b165782b3_official-source-record, says the Russian-side source was Yury Ushakov’s Kremlin-published comment. But that source is framed as an initiative “concerning a ceasefire between Russia and Ukraine for the purpose of conducting a prisoner exchange,” with the key agreement described as an exchange of 1,000 prisoners from each side during the May 9-May 11 ceasefire period. That is relevant, but it points toward a prisoner-exchange arrangement, not necessarily a general conflict pause.\n\nThe Ukrainian official-source material is narrower still. The same official-source record reports that the Ukrainian presidential decree, as captured through Ukrinform, authorized the May 9 parade in Moscow and excluded Red Square from Ukrainian weapons targeting plans for the duration of the parade. The packet itself states that this decree does not by itself state a theater-wide halt in military engagement. That distinction is central. A Red Square/parade targeting carveout is not the same thing as a general pause between two armies across the conflict.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest material is the secondary-reporting summary in ev_cf0c77f2fe52_secondary-reporting and the source list in ev_54e94624d245_primary-evidence. Those files summarize Reuters, the Guardian, NPR, CBC, and ISW as reporting a confirmed three-day ceasefire, and some reports use broader language about suspending kinetic activity. The defense does not ask the council to ignore that. We ask the council to weigh it against the packet’s own caveats: several sources tie the arrangement to Victory Day, Red Square or parade security, and a prisoner swap; the direct Ukrainian Telegram or X confirmation is not preserved in the packet; the direct Trump or White House source is not preserved; and the implementation record remains incomplete.\n\nThe unresolved-gaps file, ev_41c18aa39f56_unresolved-record-gaps, is unusually important at this opening stage. It identifies exactly the missing links that should decide the case: direct captures of the Ukrainian confirmation, the official Ukrainian decree, the U.S. announcement, battlefield or monitoring evidence about whether hostilities generally paused, and post-period official violation or implementation statements. Those are not minor housekeeping gaps. They go to whether this was a general pause or a narrow, politically timed, humanitarian and exchange-linked arrangement.\n\nSo the defense theory is simple. Plaintiff may be able to prove that there was a public May 9-May 11 arrangement, and maybe even mutual public acknowledgement of some ceasefire regime. But the qualifying proposition requires more. It requires a general halt in military engagement. If the later admitted source record shows only a prisoner-exchange window, Red Square immunity, Victory Day parade security, partial silence, or a ceasefire label followed by continuing military operations, the proposition fails.\n\nIn the evidence phases, the decisive proof should be the full official Russian text, the direct Ukrainian presidential or social-media confirmation, the U.S. source for the alleged brokered terms, and reliable reporting or monitoring of what happened across the theater on May 9, 10, and 11. Until that record proves both general scope and official mutuality, the plaintiff has not carried the burden."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"Credible reports and official confirmations establish a mutual agreement suspending all kinetic activity, satisfying the general-pause requirement despite temporal limitations and implementation issues.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement with broad diplomatic language, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements,原告has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"The plaintiff proved mutual public acknowledgement of a May 9-11 ceasefire arrangement, but the most direct Ukrainian official decree (D-1) is narrowly scoped to Red Square/parade security, the Russian official source frames it as prisoner-exchange-specific, and ISW implementation evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during the period. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The preponderance of credible reporting shows mutual agreement to a general pause suspending all kinetic activity. The Ukrainian decree addresses implementation but doesn't negate the broader agreement.","round":2,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement (PX-2) frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. While credible secondary reporting uses broad language, the direct official record and implementation evidence do not establish by preponderance a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"While credible media reports confirm mutual agreement to a May 9-11 ceasefire, the most direct official sources show narrow scope (Red Square/parade security and prisoner-exchange purpose), and ISW evidence demonstrates continued theater-wide operations. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause was reached.","round":2,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The admitted record shows a wide consensus of credible media reporting (PX-5, PX-6, PX-7, PX-8) that Russia and Ukraine mutually agreed to a ceasefire with suspension of all kinetic activity, constituting a general pause. Official Russian statements (PX-2) support the agreement, and the Ukrainian decree's narrow focus (D-1) does not negate the broader ceasefire.","round":3,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C3","rationale":"The direct Ukrainian decree was narrowly scoped to Red Square targeting, the Russian framing was prisoner-exchange-specific, and implementation evidence shows continued theater-wide operations. Plaintiff hasn't shown a qualifying general pause rather than a limited arrangement by preponderance.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C4","rationale":"The most direct official sources show narrow scope: the Ukrainian decree (D-1) addresses only Red Square/parade targeting, and the Russian statement frames the arrangement around prisoner exchange. ISW evidence (D-2) reports continued theater-wide operations during May 9-11 with activity that decreased but did not cease. Under the market's exclusion of humanitarian pauses and limited agreements, plaintiff has not carried preponderance that a qualifying general pause—rather than a short, political, exchange-linked arrangement—was reached.","round":3,"vote":"not_demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense’s best new evidence does not defeat plaintiff’s showing. It proves two narrower points: Ukraine issued a Red Square/parade decree, and the ceasefire was violated or only partly observed. Neither point changes the preponderance answer on whether an official, public, mutual general ceasefire agreement was reached.\n\nFirst, the Ukrainian decree in PX-R1 is narrower than the whole arrangement, but it is not inconsistent with the whole arrangement. It says Ukraine permitted the Moscow parade and excluded Red Square coordinates from its weapons-use plan for the parade period. That is a specific implementation act addressing the most politically sensitive target. It does not say Ukraine rejected, limited, or replaced the May 9-11 ceasefire regime that Zelenskyy was reported to have confirmed. The defense turns silence in one decree into contradiction. The better inference is additive: Ukraine made a specific Red Square order within a broader U.S.-brokered truce-and-exchange package.\n\nSecond, PX-R2 is powerful implementation evidence, but it is not agreement-formation evidence. It repeatedly describes the May 9-11 period as a ceasefire and treats continued operations as violations of that ceasefire. Its key takeaway is that forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater during the second day. That helps show breach, poor monitoring, and imperfect compliance. It does not show there was no official agreement. A violated ceasefire remains a ceasefire agreement; otherwise any party could erase a public ceasefire by breaching it immediately.\n\nPX-R2 also contains facts the defense understates. It says NASA FIRMS signatures indicated hostilities further decreased on May 10. It reports no large Russian missile packages, only 27 drones in the specified overnight/early-morning window, all downed, and several localized operations with no advance. It even notes some sectors where no ground assaults occurred on May 9 or where operations continued at a reduced pace. That is not proof of a total, perfect pause, but the proposition does not require perfection. It supports the more modest conclusion that a general ceasefire was announced and had some theater-wide operational effect, while being violated in places.\n\nThe defense’s legal move is to convert implementation failures into a scope limitation. The record does not support that conversion. The strongest scope evidence remains the common phrase preserved in PX-5, PX-6, and PX-7: suspension of all kinetic activity between Russia and Ukraine. That phrase is not Red Square-specific, not Black Sea-specific, not energy-infrastructure-specific, and not merely a future framework. The prisoner exchange and Victory Day context explain why the ceasefire happened; they do not narrow the announced operational term.\n\nNor does the direct-source gap carry the defense over the line. PX-1 allows a wide consensus of credible media reporting that an official ceasefire agreement was reached. Plaintiff supplied multiple accepted reports preserving the same official statements from Trump, Zelenskyy, and Ushakov. Those reports include the adverse facts the defense relies on, which makes their mutual-confirmation and all-kinetic-activity reporting more reliable, not less.\n\nSo the rebuttal point is simple: PX-R1 proves a specific Ukrainian parade carveout, not the absence of a broader ceasefire; PX-R2 proves violations and reduced-but-continuing activity, not the absence of an official mutual agreement. On this record, it remains more likely than not that Russia and Ukraine publicly and mutually reached a dated May 9-11 halt in military engagement broad enough to constitute a general pause, even though it was short, politically timed, and imperfectly observed."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_209acebc67ff_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-209acebc67ff","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates that Trump announced Russia and Ukraine had agreed to a three-day ceasefire and prisoner swap; reports the ceasefire included suspension of all kinetic activity; includes Zelenskyy confirmation and Kremlin confirmation/adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"209acebc67ff72b793bd3a1618a03c9cc972aeeee8cbea913f9e22b982fafca4","size_bytes":1895,"source_description":"ABC News article by Nicholas Kerr and Patrick Reevell, captured via web open/find on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines.","source_url":"https://abcnews.com/International/trump-3-day-ceasefire-prisoner-swap-occur-russia/story?id=132793171","title":"ABC News May 8 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine three-day ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e2286c9504ec_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-e2286c9504ec","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates mutual confirmation by both sides, dates May 9-11, all-kinetic-activity language, POW exchange, Zelenskyy Telegram language, and Ushakov Russian-side confirmation; also notes prior unilateral/truce context and violation history.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:00:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"e2286c9504ecbed612889913d8a8fcc1eb4e117d1156b5723c5370c068fc4640","size_bytes":1904,"source_description":"The Guardian article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 144-174.","source_url":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/may/08/trump-russia-ukraine-three-day-ceasefire-9-may","title":"Guardian May 8 2026 report on Russia and Ukraine confirming ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_c8434a93386e_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-c8434a93386e","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Independent corroboration that Russia and Ukraine agreed to three-day ceasefire and 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner swap; includes Russian aide, Zelenskyy X, Trump kinetic-activity statement, Ukrainian decree limitation, and Russian MOD adverse context.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"c8434a93386e4c1ec598c90c5bde3d00fe6315a0c690dcdb9bc0e77dae0a9172","size_bytes":1687,"source_description":"China Daily republication of Xinhua report, captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 45-69.","source_url":"https://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202605/09/WS69fe929aa310d6866eb47a63.html","title":"China Daily/Xinhua May 9 2026 report on Russia-Ukraine ceasefire"},{"evidence_id":"ev_797c6a2cd3aa_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-797c6a2cd3aa","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates Kremlin-aligned report of Russia agreeing to extend truce until May 11 and prisoner exchange; contains adverse/limiting Victory Day framing and links to Zelenskyy confirmation and official parade permission.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:01:30Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"797c6a2cd3aab56ae77ee80a8d3ba7dc8bb4463711fbc93563f780bf3f1e99b3","size_bytes":1535,"source_description":"Ukrainska Pravda article captured via web open on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract from accessible page lines 67-90.","source_url":"https://www.pravda.com.ua/eng/news/2026/05/08/8033891/","title":"Ukrainska Pravda May 8 2026 report on Kremlin agreement to Trump initiative"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4fbef7260120_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-4fbef7260120","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Direct official Ukrainian source showing the decree itself concerned permitting the May 9 Moscow parade and excluding the Red Square coordinate box from Ukrainian weapons targeting during the parade, supporting the defense argument that the official Ukrainian decree was narrow and humanitarian/parade-specific rather than a theater-wide halt.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:06:30Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"4fbef72601203596f0ff28a350bbdba79c2d535f9854578da5afdcdb873abd8f","size_bytes":1987,"source_description":"Official website of the President of Ukraine decree page, opened via web on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant page text from lines 295-314 captured as text.","source_url":"https://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3742026-59389","title":"Official Ukrainian Presidential Decree No. 374/2026 on Moscow parade and Red Square targeting"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b4bfea1a053a_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-b4bfea1a053a","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Directly addresses whether military engagement generally paused during the May 9-11 period; reports continued limited offensive operations, mutual accusations, artillery/drone/ground assault figures, NASA FIRMS signatures indicating decreased but continuing hostilities, and lack of enforcement/monitoring mechanisms.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T03:07:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"b4bfea1a053a30cb68ba9f1e476584d3ebee2a594164be4c1d2ce125e8812a29","size_bytes":3066,"source_description":"Critical Threats republication of ISW Russian Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 10, 2026, retrieved via web search/open result on 2026-06-30 UTC; relevant text extract preserved from accessible page content.","source_url":"https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/russian-offensive-campaign-assessment-may-10-2026","title":"Critical Threats/ISW May 10 2026 assessment on continued operations during ceasefire"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal correctly identifies the hard question but answers the wrong one. The defense is not arguing the abstract rule that every violation erases every ceasefire agreement. A breached ceasefire can still be a ceasefire agreement. The point is narrower: this proposition requires a publicly announced and mutually agreed halt in military engagement that constituted a general pause in the conflict. Formation, scope, and classification cannot be separated as cleanly as plaintiff proposes.\n\nD-1 is not merely an argument from silence. It is the direct Ukrainian official source now in the record, and it is affirmative about what it does: humanitarian purpose, permission for the Moscow parade, and a Red Square targeting exclusion during the parade. It does not contain the theater-wide commitment plaintiff needs. Plaintiff says this was just one implementation act within a broader arrangement, but the broader Ukrainian commitment remains proved through secondary reporting rather than the direct official Ukrainian source. Under preponderance, that matters.\n\nD-2 is likewise not just “imperfect compliance.” It reports that Russian and Ukrainian forces continued limited offensive operations across the theater throughout the second day; that activity decreased but did not cease; that tactical combat missions persisted; and that the arrangement lacked explicit enforcement, monitoring, and dispute-resolution mechanisms. Those facts bear directly on whether the arrangement constituted a general pause. A reduction in tempo is not the same as a general halt in military engagement.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest phrase remains “suspension of all kinetic activity,” preserved through the secondary reports. But the official and implementation record pulls the other way: Russian official framing around the prisoner exchange, Ukrainian official action limited to Red Square/parade security, and contemporaneous reporting of continued theater-wide operations. The council can accept that there was a public May 9-11 ceasefire label and still find that plaintiff has not shown a qualifying general pause rather than a short, political, exchange-linked and only partially observed arrangement.\n\nThat is enough for defense. The exclusions in PX-1 would mean little if any temporary truce label plus broad diplomatic phrasing qualified despite direct narrow official acts and continued operations across the conflict zone. Plaintiff has not made the qualifying characterization more likely than the non-qualifying one."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Searched exact terms from the packet and source-specific leads for May 8-9 2026 Russia-Ukraine ceasefire, Ushakov, Zelenskyy, and all-kinetic-activity language. Opened and captured relevant text from ABC News, Guardian, China Daily/Xinhua, and Ukrainska Pravda; each was submitted as source evidence. Attempted direct Kremlin retrieval at en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/79702 via curl with browser user-agent, but it produced no usable output before timeout; the case-packet official-source record remains the preserved Kremlin-path evidence. X/Twitter opened without readable page lines; Zelenskyy language is therefore preserved through submitted credible reports, not direct social capture. ISW remained unavailable through web fetch, so it is used only as summarized in the original packet, not as newly submitted source evidence. Remaining gaps: direct Ukrainian official page/social capture, direct U.S. Truth Social/White House capture, and full battlefield-monitoring implementation evidence.","title":"Plaintiff source-search ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"At the start of the argument phase, defendant inspected the updated record and read all four newly submitted plaintiff evidence extracts. Plaintiff's exhibits were treated as secondary reporting with useful quoted statements but important capture limits: no direct Zelenskyy Telegram/X artifact, no direct Truth Social/White House artifact, and mixed limiting context. Defendant searched official and adverse implementation sources identified in the opening journal. The official Ukrainian presidential decree page was reachable and was submitted as D-1. A Critical Threats/ISW May 10 assessment on continued operations during the May 9-11 period was located and submitted as D-2. Remaining unresolved gaps include the direct U.S. announcement, direct Ukrainian social confirmation beyond the narrow decree, underlying ISW footnote sources/NASA data, and complete post-period official violation statements.","title":"Defense source-chain and search ledger"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T03:43:08.105812553Z","deliberation_round":3,"member_id":"C5","opportunity_id":"deliberation:3:C5","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":894569,"role_id":"council","turn_number":21}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782790093540}]}
